{"source_key":"sha256-355a756a18981dacd0db7e3d49a0655c","record_index":165,"record_hash":"sha256:1a04bc91c8e4f527cf5bea79473e6e2037689a994e44cac66d24b1f40b2a2db1","timestamp":"2026-05-31T16:35:38.133Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"My take: **not as drawn.** AHP makes sense as an optional future ingestion source, not as the core `but-agentlog` architecture and not as a GitMeta-backed “GitButler AHP server” unless GitButler is actually hosting agents.\n\n`but-agentlog` is doing durable capture: read agent transcripts, normalize/redact them, attach GitButler branch/review/change evidence, store in GitMeta, then expose bounded projections for skim/show/Agent Trail. See [capture.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [transcript.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [write.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [environment.rs]([REDACTED:path]), and [projection.rs]([REDACTED:path]). The local-first/publish model is also very GitMeta-specific: [agentlog-local-publishing.md]([REDACTED:path]).\n\nAHP is trying to solve a different problem: a live, multi-client session protocol for agent hosts. It has JSON-RPC, root/session/terminal/changeset channels, reducers, subscriptions, replay/reconnect, tool-call lifecycle, and UI state sync. It is explicitly draft/unstable. Microsoft’s repo describes it as a “portable, standalone sessions server” protocol, with clients in Rust/TS/Swift/Kotlin and the VS Code agent host as the reference server.\n\nThe practical fit is:\n\n- **Good fit:** `but-agentlog` can add an **AHP collector** that acts as an AHP client, subscribes to an existing AHP host, and converts `SessionState`/`Turn`/`ResponsePart`[REDACTED:path] state into the current internal `TranscriptBatch`-style model.\n- **Bad fit:** making GitButler the AHP server just to persist logs. In AHP, the server owns sessions and runs/proxies the agent. A passive recorder should be a client/subscriber.\n- **Bad fit:** storing raw AHP state directly in GitMeta. It’s draft, UI-oriented, and does not encode GitButler’s target evidence, privacy/publish boundary, redaction policy, or session-to-branch verification.\n- **Maybe later:** expose GitMeta agentlogs as a read-only AHP-ish replay server for some UI. That’s a separate product, and probably awkward because AHP clients expect live session capabilities.\n\nIf agents implemented this cleanly, the shape would be:\n\n1. Agent host exposes AHP over WebSocket/stdio/Unix socket.\n2. GitButler runs `but agentlog ahp watch <endpoint>` or a background collector.\n3. Collector calls `initialize`, subscribes to `ahp-root://`, calls `listSessions`, subscribes to sessions matching `workingDirectory`[REDACTED:path]\n4. On snapshots/actions/reconnect replay, maintain a local state mirror using the AHP reducer library.\n5. On `session/turnComplete` or backfill via `fetchTurns`, map the completed turn into GitButler’s own record model.\n6. Continue capturing GitButler environment/targets locally; don’t trust AHP changesets as a replacement for branch/review/change association.\n7. Store `source_protocol = ahp`, AHP protocol version, provider/model/session URI, and redacted source snippets for debugging.\n\nSo: **keep scraping for Codex/Claude today.** It’s ugly, but it captures the agents users actually run. Track AHP, and add an adapter only when there’s a real AHP host endpoint worth consuming. Also, your diagram says “ACP Protocol” while the link is AHP; if you meant Zed-style ACP, that may be a more direct ingestion target for coding agents, but it’s still an adapter, not the GitMeta storage contract.\n\nSources: [AHP overview](https://microsoft.github.io/agent-host-protocol/specification/overview.html), [AHP session channel](https://microsoft.github.io/agent-host-protocol/specification/session-channel.html), [AHP session reference](https://microsoft.github.io/agent-host-protocol/reference/session.html), [AHP changesets](https://microsoft.github.io/agent-host-protocol/reference/changeset.html), [AHP GitHub repo](https://github.com/microsoft/agent-host-protocol), [Rust SDK](https://github.com/microsoft/agent-host-protocol/tree/main/clients/rust), [TypeScript SDK](https://github.com/microsoft/agent-host-protocol/tree/main/clients/typescript), [VS Code Agents window docs](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/agents/agents-window).","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-31T16:35:38.133Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}